   teaches: 'Stage 1 (Build): It works. Stage 2 (Write): It is maintainable. Stage 3 (Understand): It is simple. The bliss of code comes when you reach Stage 3â€”code reads like prose, intent is clear, changes are easy.'
   chapter: 'BWU Principle Chapter'
   source: ai-route-implementation-guide
   related: [cc-001, cc-007, wis-007, wis-008]

 # â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 # SECTION: DATA FORMATTING - The Art of Human-Readable Structure
 # Source: The Tao of Development - Data Formatting Chapter
 # â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

 - id: cc-012
   text: 'A student asked the master: "Should I use spaces or tabs for indentation?" The master replied: "Use spaces for consistency, tabs for flexibility, but never mix them. The real question is: Can a human read your data at 3am without weeping?"'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: readability
   level: intermediate
   tags: [codecraft, formatting, indentation, spaces, tabs, readability, koan, featured]
   teaches: 'Data formatting is not about machinesâ€”it is about humans. Choose consistency over personal preference. The best format is the one that remains readable when you are tired, when you are debugging, when you are teaching.'
   chapter: 'Data Formatting Chapter'
   koan: 'The Indentation Paradox'
   related: [cc-001, cc-002, arch-013]

 - id: cc-013
   text: 'Two spaces align, Four spaces nest deep, Tabs break the flow.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: readability
   level: beginner
   tags: [codecraft, formatting, indentation, spaces, tabs, haiku, poetry, readability]
   teaches: 'Consistency in indentation creates visual harmony. Two spaces for lists, four for nesting. Tabs introduce chaos when mixed with spaces. Choose one and honor it throughout.'
   chapter: 'Data Formatting Chapter'
   related: [cc-012, cc-001]

 - id: cc-014
   text: 'Data written for machines is noise. Data written for humans is music. The master writes data that both can readâ€”machines parse it quickly, humans understand it immediately.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: readability
   level: master
   tags: [codecraft, formatting, readability, philosophy, data, human-readable, featured]
   teaches: 'The highest form of data formatting serves both machine and human. YAML with consistent indentation, JSON with proper spacing, XML with clear structure. When data reads like prose, both parser and programmer rejoice.'
   chapter: 'Data Formatting Chapter'
   related: [cc-001, cc-012, arch-013, cc-011]

 - id: cc-015
   text: 'A gardener waters, he does not burn the field.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: patterns
   level: advanced
   tags: [codecraft, non-destructive, upsert, deletion, operations, patterns, koan, featured]
   teaches: 'Upserts grow the garden; deletion is fire. Prefer non-destructive operations by default. Create and update preserve what exists; delete destroys what was. The gardener nurtures growth, not destruction.'
   chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
   koan: 'The Gardener and the Field'
   related: [cc-001, arch-013, cc-011]

 # â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 # SECTION: DATA OPERATIONS - Sources of Truth, Upserts, and Safe Practices
 # Source: The Tao of Development - Data Operations & Migration Chapter
 # â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

 - id: cc-016
   text: 'Choose a single source of truth and let your imports converge to it, not fight it. WP is the source. Strapi is the mirror. Upserts keep the mirror aligned without smashing it.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: patterns
   level: intermediate
   tags: [codecraft, single-source-of-truth, upsert, imports, synchronization, patterns, featured]
   teaches: 'Upserts keep the mirror aligned without smashing it. Choose one source of truth and let all systems converge to it. The source defines reality; mirrors reflect it. Upserts update without destruction.'
   chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
   related: [arch-013, cc-015, qa-015]

 - id: cc-017
   text: 'Deletion must never be the default; it must be a conscious act with a visible switch. Non-destructive import is the safe baseline. Pruning (removing missing members) is an opt-in ritual, not an accident.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: patterns
   level: advanced
   tags: [codecraft, non-destructive, deletion, pruning, safety, operations, patterns, featured]
   teaches: 'Deletion must never be the default. Non-destructive import is the safe baseline. Pruning is an opt-in ritual, not an accident. Backups first, fire laterâ€”if ever.'
   chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
   related: [cc-015, cc-016, arch-027]

 - id: cc-018
   text: 'When people (or records) leave, the system should acknowledge that change, not erase their existence blindly. Prefer soft status changes (active â†’ former) over hard deletes. Keep history; change visibility.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: patterns
   level: intermediate
   tags: [codecraft, soft-delete, status-changes, history, data-integrity, patterns]
   teaches: 'A departed member is not a bug, but a story with an ending. Systems that remember endings are kinder to the truth. Prefer soft status changes over hard deletes. Keep history; change visibility.'
   chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
   related: [cc-015, cc-017, wis-011]

 - id: cc-019
   text: 'Dangerous operations belong behind flags, with dry-runs and clear naming. --prune-missing rather than hidden behavior. --prune-strategy=soft|hard rather than "guess what I did". --dry-run to rehearse before acting.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: patterns
   level: advanced
   tags: [codecraft, cli-design, safety, flags, dry-run, dangerous-operations, patterns, featured]
   teaches: 'The wise engineer makes danger optional. A good CLI offers a safe path by default and a sharp blade only when asked. Dangerous operations belong behind flags, with dry-runs and clear naming.'
   chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
   related: [cc-017, wis-012, arch-027]

 - id: cc-020
   text: 'DEV and STG are where you practice deletion and pruning. PROD is where you perform only the drills that passed. Prototype --prune-missing in DEV. Rehearse it in STG with real data. Use it in PROD only after it has become boring.'
   section: code-craft
   subsection: patterns
   level: intermediate
   tags: [codecraft, environments, dev-stg-prod, practice, safety, operations, patterns]
   teaches: 'Practice in the dojo, perform in the arena. If a command surprises you in PROD, it was not trained enough. DEV and STG are where you practice; PROD is where you perform only the drills that passed.'
   chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
   related: [cc-019, wis-013, dop-001]

- id: cc-021
  text: '"Drop and reimport" is not evil, but it is a ritual, not a routine. Use it where consequences are acceptable (DEV/STG). In PROD, prefer incremental convergence + optional prune.'
  section: code-craft
  subsection: patterns
  level: intermediate
  tags: [codecraft, migration, drop-reimport, incremental, convergence, patterns]
  teaches: '"Drop and reimport" is a ritual, not a routine. Use it where consequences are acceptable. In PROD, prefer incremental convergence. Backup, then pour slow.'
  chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
  related: [cc-016, cc-017, cc-020]

- id: cc-022
  text: 'The pot once emptied, Must be filled without a spill, Backup, then pour slow.'
  section: code-craft
  subsection: patterns
  level: beginner
  tags: [codecraft, migration, backup, haiku, poetry, safety, patterns]
  teaches: 'Migration requires care. The pot once emptied must be filled without a spill. Backup first, then pour slow. Incremental convergence beats reckless replacement.'
  chapter: 'Data Operations Chapter'
  related: [cc-021, cc-017]

- id: cc-023
  text: "Name your repository 'Project' and it shall be deleted with the same indifference you showed when naming it."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: beginner
  tags: [naming, git, humor, anti-pattern]
  teaches: 'Generic names lead to lost projects and lost grades'
  show_when: 'Student names repo "project", "my-website", or "folder"'

- id: cc-024
  text: "CamelCase in URLs is like wearing a tuxedo to a mud wrestling match. You think you look fancy, but you are just going to get dirty."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: beginner
  tags: [naming, conventions, humor]
  teaches: 'URLs and file systems prefer kebab-case; case sensitivity is a trap'
  related: [cc-028]

- id: cc-025
  text: "You put an 'Ã±' in the URL. The browser smiled, the server cried, and the git remote simply ceased to exist."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: beginner
  tags: [naming, encoding, urls, disaster]
  teaches: 'Special characters in filenames are a ticking time bomb'
  show_when: 'Student uses non-ASCII characters in filenames'

- id: cc-026
  text: "Your repository is named 'assignment-1_x7z9'. Are you a human or a captcha? The grader is unsure."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: intermediate
  tags: [naming, clarity, humor, identity]
  teaches: 'Avoid auto-generated or cryptic suffixes'

- id: cc-027
  text: "User 'dark_killer_69' pushes code. The hiring manager pulls code. The hiring manager deletes the resume. The circle of life continues."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: beginner
  tags: [identity, professionalism, career, humor]
  teaches: 'Your username is your first impression'
  show_when: 'Student uses unprofessional handles'

- id: cc-028
  text: "Use a space in a filename, and the command line will treat your file as two strangers passing in the night."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: beginner
  tags: [cli, naming, bash, suffering]
  teaches: 'Spaces in filenames break scripts and command line arguments'
  related: [cc-024]

- id: cc-029
  text: "You named the variable 'data'. I assume the function is named 'doThings'. We shall bury them together in the graveyard of ambiguity."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: intermediate
  tags: [naming, variables, ambiguity, clean-code]
  teaches: 'Vague naming is effectively no naming at all'

- id: cc-030
  text: "A repository without a clear name is like a tombstone without an inscription. We know something is buried there, but we don't care who it was."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: intermediate
  tags: [naming, documentation, morbidity]
  teaches: 'Descriptive names prevent project obsolescence'

- id: cc-031
  text: "Inconsistent casing is not a style. It is a ransom note written by a psychopath."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: naming
  level: beginner
  tags: [consistency, naming, discipline, humor]
  teaches: 'Pick one convention and stick to it or perish'

- id: cc-032
  text: "'Final_Final_v2' implies you have looked into the future and were wrong. Twice."
  section: code-craft
  subsection: versioning
  level: beginner
  tags: [git, versioning, sarcasm, anti-pattern]
  teaches: 'Git tags exist so you stop renaming files like a hoarder'
  show_when: 'Student uses "final" in filenames'

- id: dbg-005
  text: 'The debugger who debugs wisely, debugs only once; for each bug fixed in understanding will not return in code.'
  section: debugging
  subsection: mindset
  level: master
  tags: [debugging, understanding, learning, philosophy, featured]
  teaches: 'Do not just fix bugsâ€”understand them. Every bug reveals a gap in understanding. Fill the gap, and the bug will not return. Debugging is not about fixing codeâ€”it is about fixing understanding.'
  chapter: 'Route Implementation Chapter'
  source: ai-route-implementation-guide
  related: [dbg-004, wis-001, dbg-002]

- id: ux-004
  text: 'The master teaches by example, not by perfection.'
  section: ux
  subsection: philosophy
  level: master
  tags: [ux, teaching, example, philosophy, featured]
  teaches: 'Documentation is a living document, born from real implementation experience. It evolves as new patterns emerge. The master teaches through working examples, not theoretical perfection.'
  chapter: 'Route Implementation Chapter'
  source: ai-route-implementation-guide
  related: [wis-001, cc-001, arch-014]

